<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,908,1187]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,460,908,934]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Supplemental description</emphasis>
. Size and shape. Length: male (n=4) = 23.5–26.7, female (n=7) = 24.2–26.8; width: male = 10.4–12.2, female = 10.7–11.8. Body narrow.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="586" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,908,1187]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,462,980,1006]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">External morphology.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[470,531,980,1006]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Head</emphasis>
: eyes triangular, with lateral borders straight; anteoculus as long as interoculus, about 0.94–0.98× (
<figureCitation box="[368,459,1016,1042]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1847,1871]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,522,1821]" captionTargetId="figure-169@2.[152,1436,522,1821]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Diagnostic characters of the Belostoma fittkaui group:A—lateral view of the head showing the condition of articles II and III of the labium and prosternal keel; B—ventral view of abdomen showing the pilosity of segments II–VII; C—dorsal view of head and pronotum of Belostoma fittkaui; D—dorsal view of head and pronotum of B. sayagoi. ant = anteoculus, con = connexivum, int = interoculus, lab = labium, prk = prosternal keel, pro = pronotum, ste = sternites. The scale bar applies only to C and D." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4612920" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4612920/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Fig. 1D</figureCitation>
); vertex with a poorly elevated carina; article II of labium distinctly shorter than III, about 0.58–0.68×. 
<emphasis box="[366,447,1052,1078]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Thorax</emphasis>
: prosternal keel quite elevated with apex rounded, projecting forward; pronotum trapezoidal with lateral margins straight and a narrow fold extending to posterior portion; fore femur slender, subequal in width to middle femur; scutellum distinctly carinate. 
<emphasis box="[767,873,1124,1150]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Abdomen</emphasis>
: pilosity entirely covering sterna and connexivum, including second through seventh segments.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4612922" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4612922" box="[151,1274,1838,1862]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4612922/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="586" startId="3.[151,250,1838,1862]" targetBox="[152,1436,1210,1814]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1274,1838,1862]" box="[151,1274,1838,1862]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,275,1838,1862]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">FIGURE 2.</emphasis>
Habitus of holotypes and labels: A – 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Schnack" authorityYear="1976" box="[649,834,1838,1862]" class="Insecta" family="Belostomatidae" genus="Belostoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fittkaui">
<emphasis box="[649,834,1838,1862]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Belostoma fittkaui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and its labels; B – 
<taxonomicName authorityName="De Carlo" authorityYear="1966" box="[1022,1129,1839,1862]" class="Insecta" family="Belostomatidae" genus="Belostoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sayagoi">
<emphasis box="[1022,1129,1839,1862]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">B. sayagoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and its labels.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1908,2043]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,376,1908,1934]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Male genitalia.</emphasis>
Dorsal arms of phallosoma convergent, covering lateral margins of diverticulum and extending to distal portion of diverticulum in dorsal view; phallosoma slightly curved downward; diverticulum with a poorly developed ventral protuberance in lateral view; diverticulum trapezoidal, with lateral margins straight, becoming abruptly narrow in mesal portion in ventral view.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="587" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,150,573]" pageId="4" pageNumber="587">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,150,176]" pageId="4" pageNumber="587">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Article II of the labium distinctly shorter than III and about 0.58–0.68×, pilosity entirely covering the sterna and connexivum, and the body narrow about 2.3× as long as broad are diagnostic for this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
